This is exactly the reason why some snakes seem to have venom with overkill potency.

You hear about snakes like the Inland Taipan of Australia (most venomous snake in the world) and how a single bite could drop 100 adult humans.

It seems like overkill, but you need to remember that snake venom evolved for its natural prey and predators, not for humans. Because we haven't been bitten enough over thousands of years (at least by the elapids that seem to have the most potent venom) we have not evolved a significant resistance to it.

On the other hand, snake prey and predators are the primary targets for their venom, and have been in an arms race with snakes for millions of years. They develop resistance to the venom, and the snake evolves more potent venom in response.

There is a good chance that there are plenty of small mammal and bird species in Australia that have very high resistances to its famously deadly snakes. And that goes for the natural prey of any venomous snake species around the world.

This is also the reason why ld50 is not a perfect indicator of venom toxicity. While it has its uses, lab rats are not the natural prey of the venomous snakes being tested.

Funny, I remember seeing a SciShow video about this. From what I remember of it, the scorpion’s venom attaches to the base of pain receptor nerves and makes them go off constantly. The mouse, instead of the typical way of evolving an immunity (changing the pain receptor so the toxin can’t bind it), has a change in something further up the nerve that makes it also bind the toxin; thus, while the toxin does start up the pain sensation, it also ends up clogging up the nerve to prevent the signal.
